# CyberTriage to Timesketch - Cursor Rules
# =========================================

## Project Overview
Pure Go tool that converts CyberTriage forensic capture files (.json.gz) to Timesketch JSONL format for timeline analysis. Uses a custom byte-level streaming JSON parser for memory-efficient processing of multi-GB captures.

## Development Guidelines

### Go Environment
- Go 1.21+ required
- Module path: `github.com/NCLGISA/ct-to-timesketch`
- Build: `go build -o ct-to-timesketch ./cmd/ct-to-timesketch`

### Code Style
- Follow standard Go conventions (gofmt, golint)
- Use type hints and error returns consistently
- Document exported functions with godoc comments

### Project Structure
- Entry point: `cmd/ct-to-timesketch/main.go`
- Streaming parser: `internal/scanner/`
- Event converter: `internal/converter/`
- Forensic extractors: `internal/extractors/` (one package per extractor)
- Hayabusa post-processing: `internal/postprocess/`
- Cache/decompression: `internal/cache/`
- Progress output: `internal/progress/`
- Post-processing scripts: `scripts/` (Python utilities for JSONL analysis)
- Data type schemas: `schemas/`

### Sensitive Data Handling
- NEVER commit capture files (*.json.gz) - they contain forensic data
- NEVER commit generated reports (*.jsonl, *.html)
- NEVER commit the compiled binary (ct-to-timesketch)
- NEVER commit test_results.md (contains client hostnames)
- Test data should stay in ignored directories (captures/, reports/, outdated/, artifacts/)

### Running the Tool
```bash
# Build
go build -o ct-to-timesketch ./cmd/ct-to-timesketch

# Run (all extractors run automatically)
./ct-to-timesketch captures/sample.json.gz

# With Hayabusa threat detection
./ct-to-timesketch captures/sample.json.gz --hayabusa

# Cloud-only modes
./ct-to-timesketch captures/entra_export.json.gz --entra
./ct-to-timesketch captures/mdo_export.json.gz --mdo
```

### Testing Changes
- Run full test suite: `./test_all_captures.sh`
- Test against individual captures in `captures/`
- Output goes to `reports/<hostname>_timeline.jsonl`

### Versioning
- CalVer format: YYYY.MM.DD.BUILD (e.g., 2026.03.10.1)

### Git Workflow
- Work on feature branches for new extractors
- Keep commits focused and well-documented
- The .gitignore is configured to protect sensitive data
